blic schooling. The War That Wasn't tells a different story, arguing that in nineteenth-century New York State a civil system of democratic, local control led to adjustments and compromises far more than discord and bitter conflict. In the decades after the Civil War, New Yorkers from rural, one-room schools to big city districts hammered out a variety of ways to reconcile public education and religious diversity. This book recounts their stories in delightful and compelling detail. The common school system of New York State managed to keep the peace during a time of religious and ethnic pluralism, before sweeping educational reforms ended many of these compromises by the turn of the twentieth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aChurch and educationzNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aChurch and statezNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 0aReligion in the public schoolszNew York (State)xHistoryy19th century. 4aEducation : Education. 4aEducation : History of Education. 4aHistory : History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aEDUCATION / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013z978311148737340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780791484463423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780791484463/original  a978-3-11-148737-3  SUNY Press eBook Package  Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles